	Set set = mySet.getValues();
}

I need some help here.  The test is fundamentally different.  The old test actually tested if the module components could be loaded.  This new test just checks if the ModuleCoreNature exists on the project.  I agree this is a much faster test but is it sufficient for clients?  I need someone that knows this code better than I to answer this question before I approve.

BTW, the test could be simplified as well to just the following:

public boolean exists() {
		IProject project = getProject();
  return ModuleCoreNature.isFlexibleProject(project);
}

The test for project.isAccessible() is not necessary since this is done in ModuleCoreNature.isFlexibleProject(...).  You cannot test for a nature unless the project is accessible.

We have an editor action that extends from org.eclipse.ui.actions.ActionDelegate. During our memory usage analysis, we found that our editor could not be garbagge collected due to a reference in org.eclipse.ui.internal.ObjectPluginAction. This object always has a reference the to last opened editor.

By studying org.eclipse.ui.internal.ObjectPluginAction, it looks like variable activePart is needed only because it is used in initDelegate() method. However, it seems a bit odd to set the activePart in the init method. Furthermore, during the initialization, activePart is almost always null, the setActivePart() would not be called anyway. Hence, it leads to my suspicious that the activePart variable may not be necessary.

If it is indeed needed, be consider a way to clear the reference when the editor is disposed, so that we would not have to manually clean up the reference in our action, like the following:

public class MyAction extends org.eclipse.ui.actions.ActionDelegate {
 ....
 public void dispose() {
  if (action instanceof org.eclipse.ui.internal.ObjectPluginAction) {
     ((ObjectPluginAction) action).selectionChanged(StructuredSelection.EMPTY);
     ((ObjectPluginAction) action).setActivePart(null);
  }
 }
}

Please also note that the same problem happens to the selection variable in org.eclipse.ui.internal.PluginAction, which I think could potentially removed.

Thanks for the consideration.

